    <text>
        <body>
            <div>
                <opener>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I should have answered your Favours of 17<hi rend="superscript">th.</hi> Ultimo
                    sooner being in expectation of hearing from <persName ref="pe0156">M<hi rend="superscript">r.</hi> Low</persName>, which has not happened, so
                    postponed it no longer: since no better can be gained for <bibl type="authorial">
                        <title ref="bi0058">his M.S.</title>
                    </bibl> I intirely submit to your
                    Management &amp; do suppose the Compiler must <sic>acquiece</sic> since proper
                    Authority was consigned to you, it shall give me much pleasure to hear <add place="above">soon</add> of this Work going to the Press and then it's
                    Publication; what Copies are laid aside for <persName ref="pe0156">M<hi rend="superscript">r.</hi> Low</persName> I shall use my best Influence
                    to promote the Sale of for his Advantage: doubting not but he stands in need of
                    Favour &amp;<hi rend="superscript">c.</hi>
                </p>
                <p>Our <sic>Cropt</sic> is luxuriant, some of it very unripe yet, but the best of it
                    cut down and as the weather has been very favourable mostly got into the
                    Barn-yard; so that we have a similar prospect of Plenty as prevails with you,
                    Little or no Fruit this Year.</p>
                <p>The Account you give of the <bibl type="authorial">
                        <title ref="bi0580">American
                            Ph. Transactions</title>
                    </bibl> is agreeable, heartily do I wish you
                    every valuable communication<del rend="oversrtike">s</del> from any Quarter to
                    augment your <hi rend="underline">
                        <placeName ref="pl1175">Arctic</placeName>
                        Inquiries</hi>, a new Edition of this Zoology may, I hope, be at no great
                        distance.<note type="editorial">Probably a reference to Pennant's 1787 <bibl type="editorial">
                            <title ref="bi0021">
                                <hi rend="italic">Supplement to the
                                Arctic Zoology</hi>
                            </title>
                        </bibl> â€” the first volume of
                        <bibl type="editorial">
                            <title ref="bi0022">
                                <hi rend="italic">Arctic Zoology</hi>
                            </title>
                        </bibl> was published in 1784.
                    </note>
                </p>
                <p>I heartily wish the present bustle of impending War to soon subside, the
                    Hollanders have no great reason to boast of their former Conduct from the
                    consequences they presently feel, it is my hope &amp; wish that <persName ref="pe0236">your Son</persName> may find a peacable satisfactory excursion on
                    <placeName ref="pl1176">the Continent</placeName>, without the smallest
                    interruption to his Inquiries, which when performed may his Return to you
                    increase your happyness &amp; Pleasure.</p>
                <p>I am in hopes of picking up some Anecdotes of our late misfortunate
                    Circumnavigator <persName ref="pe0045">Cap<hi rend="superscript">t.</hi>
                        Cook</persName> of ever estimable memory, <persName ref="pe0574">his Father</persName> was a Native of
                    <placeName ref="pl0705">Scotland</placeName>, born at <placeName ref="pl1177">Ednam</placeName> in the <sic>Nighbourhood</sic> of <placeName ref="pl0415">Kelso</placeName>, more particulars I am in hopes of shortly, understand
                    <persName ref="pe0057">his Widow</persName> enjoys a comfortable Annuity.</p>
                <p>Wishing you health &amp; every prosperity</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>I am <lb/>D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Sir <lb/>Your most obed<hi rend="superscript">t.</hi> Serv<hi rend="superscript">t.</hi>
                    </salute>
                    <signed>
                        <persName ref="pe0228">GPaton</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName ref="pl0076">Edinburgh</placeName> 9 October <lb/>1784.</dateline>
            </div>
            <div>

                <p>
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Thomas Pennant Esq<hi rend="superscript">r.</hi>
                        </addrLine>
